The AP/IB Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy major prep:

  • A score of 4-5 on the AP Microeconomics exam is equivalent to Econ 1 (if taken before spring 2021) and can be used in place of the microeconomics course.
  • A score of 5 on the AP Microeconomics exam is equivalent to Econ 1 (if taken after spring 2021) and can be used in place of the microeconomics course.
  • A score of 4-5 on the AP Macroeconomics exam is equivalent to Econ 2 (if taken before spring 2021) and can be used in place of the macroeconomics course.
  • A score of 5 on the AP Macroeconomics exam is equivalent to Econ 2 (if taken after spring 2021) and can be used in place of the macroeconomics course.
  • A score of 5 on the AP Calculus AB exam or 4 on the BC exam is equivalent to Math 31A and can be used in place of the first calculus course.
  • A score of 5 on the AP BC Calculus exam is equivalent to Math 31AB and can be used in place of both calculus courses.
  • A score of 6 or 7 on IB HL exam is equivalent with Econ 1 & 2 (if taken after Nov 2013) and may be used in place of both econ courses.

The Economics BA program helps students examine how society produces and consumes goods, and it analyzes many real-world issues such as international trade, poverty, taxes, crime, and education. The curriculum provides students with thorough training in both theoretical and empirical approaches to real world problems, and it provides a framework in which to analyze human behavior. 


Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major. THIS MAJOR IS HIGHLY SELECTIVE and demand for this major significantly exceeds space available. All preparatory courses must be completed. You must be admitted directly into this major and you will not be able to change into this major after admission to UCLA.


To be considered for this major, all of the preparatory courses listed here must be completed by the spring before transfer, but students are STRONGLY ENCOURAGED to complete all preparatory courses by the fall term prior to admission:

  • One course in Macroeconomics,
  • One course in Microeconomics,
  • One year of Calculus (from math/physical science sequence), and

All courses must be taken for a letter grade.


For more information regarding this major and UCLA's selection process, visit https://econ.ucla.edu and https://admission.ucla.edu.
